column4:
It's basically of no benefit to me.  I'm not being compensated, it is going to take up a reasonable amount of my time (at least a few hours), and since I'm 44 years old and grew up with my elderly relatives, I have a pretty good idea of what kind of health risks I'm going to face as I grow older - in fact I'm starting to experience them now - so whatever the analysis reveals is unlikely to be very surprising or helpful. I don't particularly care about how much it benefits mankind or science, so that's out too.\
\
There's also the issue of (slight) risk, my information being made public, discrimination, or the chance I commit some crime and it ends up implicating me.  None of these things would dissuade me if I felt I would receive some benefit from participating, but since I already have decided i won't and don't want to do it, they're just additional reasons not to.
column45: It was well organized and laid out in a logical manner; when I was answering the questions, I could usually anticipate where the information would be found.
column46: It had a lot of gray areas concerning risks I *might* run; my information might be legally or illegally compromised, revealing data to third parties might disclose my identity, law enforcement might get access to my information, insurance companies might discriminate against me. If I weren't already disinclined to participate, the lack of detail about those risks might give me pause.

column4: While I would love to know my genomic trait data, there is too much risk involved with participating in this study.
column45: I don't think there was a single thing that I liked or enjoyed about the consent form. It was extremely long and very hard to find information to refer back to.
column46: Everything. The length of the consent form, the amount of time it took to read, was hard to find information.

column4: It sounds interesting, and I don't see any particular risk to me.
column45: I like that it was broken up into sub sections with titles that clearly summarized the information contained in that section. I also really liked how the benefits and risks section was broken up. I felt that I was very well informed of both the benefits and the risks of this study.
column46: I feel like some of the information about who has what kind of access to my data is a little scattered through the consent form.

column4: The cons outweigh the pros in this situation. The entire process seems to take while and there is too much to worry about,  such as hackers and your information being leaked somehow.
column45: I like how it was broken down into sections and each section was labeled with bold letters to let the reader know what the section consisted of.
column46: Some of the wording seemed repetitive and I got confused a little with that.

column4: Because i am not sure of this and there is no compensation for my time.
column45: I liked the clearness and understandability of the consent form presented here.
column46: It seemed like there was more disadvantages than advantages for me to take the time to do all this.

column4: It seems safe enough and I don't have a reason not to trust those who ask for my consent.
column45: I didn't have a great deal of trouble understanding the consent form.
column46: It's far too long. There has to be a way to get across this information without it seeming like a giant info dump.

column4: There are too many things that could go wrong and it's too open to outsiders hacking the information.
column45: It is written in clear language and is itemized by categories.
column46: It's too long and drawn out. It needs to be compacted to be more readable.

column4: The study is very clear about its limits and terms, and there is nothing being shared that I contend with.
column45: It was mostly clear about what needed clarification.
column46: It was kind of difficult to search for specific information afterwards.

column4: I would not participate in this study because of concerns about privacy and a lack of significant benefits to me.
column45: It was reasonably clear and straightforward.
column46: It didn't seem to offer sufficient guarantees against a possible breach of privacy.

column4: I would participate because this information could help understand genetic syndromes and genetic links to diseases. This will help future medical research. Also, I think it could be useful to understand my own personal genomics. I also like the idea that you can withdraw your data in the future.
column45: It was presented in a way that made it easy to find the information I was looking for. The way it was written made it easy to understand. I liked the outline at the top.
column46: I would have liked more information about the possible risks. More details and more examples.

column4: I believe that the benefits outweigh the risks of the study. It is unlikely that any personal information would be revealed, and as far as finding out something unpleasant about a potential health condition, I feel it is better to know and be prepared and proactive, and possibly prevent the actual disease from occurring. I would also like the genealogical information.
column45: I like the way that it is written in an FAQ format, so it is easy to find exactly what you are looking for. I also really like that fact that it is written in plain English rather than legal speak. Some consent forms have to be read over and over as you try to figure out the legal terms; this one is much easier to understand.
column46: I didn't see anything that I didn't like, honestly. The consent form seems to cover all possible problems and is very open about how knowing these results could affect you. I guess an option to print for my records is the only thing I found missing, but that would probably be there in an actual consent setting.

column4: I would be very interested in seeing my ancestry as well as my carrier status and likelihood of developing diseases. I can withdraw if I choose to so the risks are very low. (although my data will be used if already used in a study)
column45: I liked the numbered FAQ's. It made it easy to find answers to common questions and then provided even more in depth answers
column46: It was a bit long but that is pretty standard to consent forms

column4: It seems like an interesting study with low risk to me. It isn't something I would pay to do and would be useful information to know. Might as well.
column45: It was presented logically to answer questions and it was comprehensive
column46: Like all forms, there was some legalese.

column4: I would most likely not participate in this study.  It seems to me that the potential risks are greater and are more significant than the possible benefits, especially considering that the benefits are inconclusive, and only can be interpreted in very probabilistic and relative terms.   Good, regular routine preventative health care, paired with healthy, consistent lifestyle choices, behaviors, and postive environmental conditions perhaps offer much more substantive, predictable protection against various afflictions and diseases, even though the genomic data analysis in question would certainly prove worthwhile as an additional interpretative tool in managing one's personal and family health.
column45: The consent form presented contained a great deal of useful information.   However, it could have been organized and topically presented in a more informative, easier to read format.   I would have liked to see the use of a much more structured approach, using more headings, subtopics, and enermerated lists and items.  Also, links could and should be added to provide respondents with additional detail on the current state of various complicated topics and overall, genomic research, (what other national bodies, countries, etc, are engaged in such research, and what has been their experience?) and also on the topic of the potential advantanges and disadvantages of respondent participation.   There remained too many unanswered questions concerning the privacy and security of the genomic data collected that make me uneasy, for example.   I would want to know more about my rights, the current law surrounding this topic, and what concrete precautions will be taken to assure the abolute integ
column46: It is sometimes hard to follow because it is overly general about the section or topic under discussion at any one point.  I often felt like it had been over-edited.  Perhaps an intitial abstract, or executive summary might be best presented first, and then a more structured document offered, with links, should the user care to delve deeper into the subject matter presented.  Also, video content could be developed as a companion piece in complementing the content of the provided consent form.
